eals how social, technological, institutional, and military dynamics interplay to catalyze modern surgical innovation. Author Justin Barr examines each of these phenomena through the complementary perspectives of academic historian andclinical surgeon, marshaling extensive research and incisive analysis into a broadly applicable model that helps frame, illuminate, and forecast change in surgery. Justin Barr received his PhD in History from Yale University and his MD from the University of Virginia. He is currently in residency for general surgery at Duke University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArteriesxSurgeryxHistoryy19th century. 0aArteriesxSurgeryxHistoryy20th century. 0aArteriesxSurgeryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSurgery, MilitaryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aHistory of Science & Medicine. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  a1880-1960.  aamputation.  aaneurysms.  aarteries.  acholesterol buildup.  aclinical surgeon.  acomplex factors.  adamaged vessels.  ahealthcare history.  ahealthcare innovation.  ahistorical research.  ainnovation.  ainstitutional development.  ainterdisciplinary.  alimb preservation.  amedical advancements.  amedical breakthroughs.  amedical education.  amedical evolution.  amedical expertise.  amedical heritage.  amedical history.  amedical literature.  amedical narratives.  amedical perspectives.  amedical professionals.  amedical progress.  amedical science.  amedical technology.  amedical transformation.  amilitary influence.  apatient care.  asocial dynamics.  asurgical history.  asurgical innovation.  asurgical interventions.  asurgical practices.  asurgical procedures.  asurgical repair.  asurgical techniques.  atechnological advancements.  avascular diseases.  